filter()

Call Signature

  filter<T, S>(this, match): Cheerio<S>

Defined in: src/api/traversing.ts:735

Iterates over a cheerio object, reducing the set of selector elements to those that match the selector or
pass the function's test.

This is the definition for using type guards; have a look below for other ways to invoke this method. The
function is executed in the context of the selected element, so this refers to the current element.

Type Parameters

• T

• S

Parameters

this

Cheerio<T>

match

(this, index, value) => value is S

Value to look for, following the rules above.

Returns

Cheerio<S>

The filtered collection.

Example

    $('li')
      .filter(function (i, el) {
        // this === el
        return $(this).attr('class') === 'orange';
      })
      .attr('class'); //=> orange

[][]

See

https://api.jquery.com/filter/

Call Signature

  filter<T, S>(this, match): Cheerio<S extends string ? Element : T>

Defined in: src/api/traversing.ts:774

Iterates over a cheerio object, reducing the set of selector elements to those that match the selector or
pass the function's test.

- When a Cheerio selection is specified, return only the elements contained in that selection.
- When an element is specified, return only that element (if it is contained in the original selection).
- If using the function method, the function is executed in the context of the selected element, so this
  refers to the current element.

Type Parameters

• T

• S

Parameters

this

Cheerio<T>

match

S

Value to look for, following the rules above. See AcceptedFilters.

Returns

Cheerio<S extends string ? Element : T>

The filtered collection.

Examples

    $('li').filter('.orange').attr('class');
    //=> orange

[][]

    $('li')
      .filter(function (i, el) {
        // this === el
        return $(this).attr('class') === 'orange';
      })
      .attr('class'); //=> orange

[][]

See

https://api.jquery.com/filter/

